Datas

Load datas

Datas extract from : H2_anat_spike_distance.txt

file_path = "/Volumes/Backup DD/From_BAIE/Julien/Connectivity/Scripts/R/Datas/H2_anat_spike_distance.txt"
datas <- read.table(file_path, header = TRUE)

Preprocessing

There is 3 Anatomy levels:
NC-NC, DT-NC, AT-NC, DT-DC, AT-DC, NC-DC, DC-NC, DC-DC, DT-OT, AT-OT, DT-AT, AT-AT, NC-OT, NC-AT, OT-OT, OT-AT, OT-NC, OT-DC, DC-DT, DC-AT, DC-OT, NC-DT

We reduce the dimension.
For instance DC-NC is the same than NC-DC.
And we remove the AT levels (to ovoid the redundancy in the datas).

datas %>%
  mutate(Organisation = case_when(Organisation == "0" ~ "0",
                                  Organisation == "1" ~ "1"),
         Anatomy = case_when(Anatomy == "NC-NC" ~ "NC-NC",
                             Anatomy == "DC-DC" ~ "DC-DC",
                             Anatomy == "DT-DT" ~ "DT-DT",
                             Anatomy == "OT-OT" ~ "OT-OT",
                             Anatomy == "DC-NC" ~ "NC-DC",
                             Anatomy == "NC-DC" ~ "NC-DC",
                             Anatomy == "DC-DT" ~ "DT-DC",
                             Anatomy == "DT-DC" ~ "DT-DC",
                             Anatomy == "DT-NC" ~ "NC-DT",
                             Anatomy == "NC-DT" ~ "NC-DT",
                             Anatomy == "OT-DT" ~ "DT-OT",
                             Anatomy == "DT-OT" ~ "DT-OT",
                             Anatomy == "OT-NC" ~ "NC-OT",
                             Anatomy == "NC-OT" ~ "NC-OT",
                             Anatomy == "OT-DC" ~ "DC-OT",
                             Anatomy == "DC-OT" ~ "DC-OT"),
         EZ = case_when(EZ == "0" ~ "0",
                        EZ == "1" ~ "1",
                        EZ == "2" ~ "1")) %>%
  drop_na(EZ) %>%
  drop_na(Anatomy) %>%
  mutate(Anatomy = as.factor(Anatomy),
         Organisation = as.factor(Organisation),
         EZ = as.factor(EZ),
         Spasm = as.factor(Spasm), 
         Pat_name = as.factor(Pat_name),
         Channels = as.factor(Channels)) -> datas

How many datas ?

Here we visualize the data from the contingency table or two-way frequency table.
In this plot, the size represent the proportional value.
For instance, in the first plot.For DC-OT anatomic level, there is a huge unbalance number of EZ values. With a very few EZ egual 1.
This means that we cant analyse the interaction between Anatomic and EZ factors.
Because there is a very low statistic power (not enough datas within each anatomic levels).

Is not the same for Spasm VS anatomic and Organisation VS Anatomy.

mosaicplot(xtabs(H2~Anatomy+EZ, datas), 
           color = TRUE,
           border = "chocolate",
           main = "EZ")

           main = "Organisation")

Distribution

Then, we explore the nature of your variable of interest: the H2.
This is the plot of the H2 distribution.
One color by anatomic level.
Clearly, its not a normal distribution. For several reasons :
- Datas were borned, there is not 0 value
- And the shape is not a gaussian with a pic not centered

This means that we cant use a parametric statistic like anova.
Typically many people use a log transform. So datas look like a normal distribution.
But not, with log transform you can get a normal shape distribution but this is artificial, you cant create the lost information of the left of the distribution. Distribution was cut before 0 and its lost for ever.

Later, in our model, we will use a Gamma log description of the error distribution.

datas %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=H2, fill = Anatomy, color = Anatomy)) +
  geom_density(alpha = 0.3) +
   theme(legend.position = "none")

Statistic

To describe H2 we use a model with :

  • Main effect:
    EZ
    Spasm
    C_Tubers
    Toto_Tuber
    Organisation
    Age
    Distance
    Anatomy
    Spike_rate

  • Interaction
    Anatomy*Spasm

We use a GLMM model with Gamma log description of the error distribution.
The random effect is simpler with only one intercept by patient to take into account variability across patients and non-independence of data within each patients.

Here the models formula:
\[\begin{aligned} \operatorname{H2}_{i} &\sim N \left(\mu, \sigma^2 \right) \\ \mu &=\alpha + \beta_{1}(Age) + \beta_{1}(Organisation) + \beta_{1}(C\_Tubers) + \\ &~~~~~~~~~~~~~ \beta_{1}(Toto\_Tubers) + \beta_{1}(\operatorname{Distance}) + \beta_{2}(\operatorname{Spike\_rate}) + \beta_{3}(\operatorname{EZ}) + \\ &~~~~~~~~~~~~~\beta_{4}(\operatorname{Anatomy}) + \beta_{5}(\operatorname{Spasm}) + \beta_{5}(\operatorname{Anatomy}:\operatorname{Spasm}) \\ \alpha &\sim N \left(\beta{0} + \beta{S} \right) \end{aligned}\]

For Subject S = 1 : n

We fit 2 models with exactly the same factors but datas change:
- With the 6 levels of anatomy (interzone)
- With the grouping of anatomy in 3 levels (intrazone)

INTRAZONE model

3 Anatomy levels

NC-NC : NC
DC-DC : DC
DT-OT & OT-OT : TUBERS

Model definition

datas %>%
  filter(Anatomy == "NC-NC" | Anatomy == "DC-DC" | Anatomy == "OT-OT" | Anatomy == "DT-OT") %>%
  mutate(Anatomy = case_when(Anatomy == "NC-NC" ~ "NC-NC",
                             Anatomy == "DC-DC" ~ "DC-DC",
                             Anatomy == "DT-OT" ~ "Tuber",
                             Anatomy == "OT-OT" ~ "Tuber"),
         Anatomy = as.factor(Anatomy)) %>%
  data.frame() -> data.intra

model.intra <- mixed(H2 ~ Organisation +
                       scale(Distance) + 
                       scale(Spike_rate) +
                       scale(C_Tubers) + scale(Toto_Tubers) + scale(Age) + EZ +
                       Anatomy*Spasm + 
                  (1|Pat_name),
                  data = data.intra,
                  method = "LRT",
                  family = Gamma(link = "log"),
                  verbose = FALSE,
                  control = glmerControl(optimizer="bobyqa"))
## Fitting 11 (g)lmer() models:
## [...........]
library(equatiomatic) 
equatiomatic::extract_eq(model.intra$full_model, wrap = 2)
$$ \[\begin{aligned} \alpha_{j} &\sim N \left(\gamma_{0}^{\alpha} + \gamma_{1}^{\alpha}(\operatorname{Organisation}_{\operatorname{1}}) + \gamma_{2}^{\alpha}(\operatorname{scale(C\_Tubers)}) + \gamma_{3}^{\alpha}(\operatorname{scale(Toto\_Tubers)}) + \gamma_{4}^{\alpha}(\operatorname{scale(Age)}) + \gamma_{5}^{\alpha}(\operatorname{Spasm}_{\operatorname{1}}) + \gamma_{6}^{\alpha}(\operatorname{Anatomy}_{\operatorname{1}} \times \operatorname{Spasm}_{\operatorname{1}}) + \gamma_{7}^{\alpha}(\operatorname{Anatomy}_{\operatorname{2}} \times \operatorname{Spasm}_{\operatorname{1}}), \sigma^2_{\alpha_{j}} \right) \text{, for Pat\_name j = 1,} \dots \text{,J} \end{aligned}\] \[ \] \[\begin{aligned} \alpha_{j} &\sim N \left(\gamma_{0}^{\alpha} + \gamma_{1}^{\alpha}(\operatorname{Organisation}_{\operatorname{1}}) + \gamma_{2}^{\alpha}(\operatorname{scale(C\_Tubers)}) + \gamma_{3}^{\alpha}(\operatorname{scale(Toto\_Tubers)}) + \gamma_{4}^{\alpha}(\operatorname{scale(Age)}) + \gamma_{5}^{\alpha}(\operatorname{Spasm}_{\operatorname{1}}) + \gamma_{6}^{\alpha}(\operatorname{Anatomy}_{\operatorname{1}} \times \operatorname{Spasm}_{\operatorname{1}}) + \gamma_{7}^{\alpha}(\operatorname{Anatomy}_{\operatorname{2}} \times \operatorname{Spasm}_{\operatorname{1}}), \sigma^2_{\alpha_{j}} \right) \text{, for Pat\_name j = 1,} \dots \text{,J} \end{aligned}\]

$$

Model check quality

R2

The marginal 2 considers only the variance of the fixed effects (without the random effects).
While the conditional 2 takes both the fixed and random effects into account.

library(performance)
r2(model.intra$full_model) -> a

Hosmer-Lemeshow Goodness-of-Fit Test
Small p-values mean that the model is a poor fit.

Anatomy:Spasm

Display of raw and models predicted values to better understand how the effects are expressed (qualitativly).
Predicted values (marginal effects) with confidence interval for specific model terms.

data.intra %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=Anatomy, y=H2, fill = Spasm)) +
  geom_boxplot(alpha = 0.4) +
    coord_cartesian(ylim=c(0.04, 0.20)) +
  scale_fill_grey() + 
  theme_classic() +
  theme(legend.position = "right",
        axis.title.x = element_text(size = 14, face = "bold"),
        axis.text.x = element_text(face = "bold", size = 12, angle = 45, hjust = 1),
        axis.text.y = element_text(face = "bold", size = 12, angle = 0, hjust = 1)) +
  labs(x = "",
       y = "H2") +
  ggtitle("Raw datas")-> p1 


plot_model(model.intra$full_model,
           type = "pred",
           colors = "gs",
           terms = c("Anatomy", "Spasm")) +
    coord_cartesian(ylim=c(0.04, 0.20)) +
  theme_classic() +
  theme(legend.position = "right",
        axis.title.x = element_text(size = 14, face = "bold"),
        axis.text.x = element_text(face = "bold", size = 12, angle = 45, hjust = 1),
        axis.text.y = element_text(face = "bold", size = 12, angle = 0, hjust = 1)) +
  labs(x = "",
       y = "H2") +
  ggtitle("Predicted Values") -> p2

Here, the statistic values for all comparisons (quantitativly).

emm.intra <- emmeans(model.intra, ~ Spasm | Anatomy, type = "response") 

des_cont <- list("Spasm 0-1" = c(1, -1))

contrast(emm.intra, des_cont, adjust = "FDR") %>%
  data.frame()  %>%
  mutate(`(FDR)` = round(p.value,4)) %>%
  dplyr::select(-df, -z.ratio, -ratio, -SE, -p.value) -> cc.01

contrast(emm.intra, des_cont, adjust = "none") %>%
  data.frame() %>%
  dplyr::select(-df, -z.ratio) %>%
  mutate(p.value = round(p.value,4),
         ratio = round(ratio,4),
         SE = round(SE,4)) %>%
  right_join(cc.01) %>%
  mutate(`-` = case_when(`(FDR)` > 0.05 ~ ".",
                        `(FDR)` < 0.05 ~ "*")) 
##    contrast Anatomy  ratio     SE p.value  (FDR) -
## 1 Spasm 0-1   DC-DC 0.6788 0.1176  0.0254 0.0254 *
## 2 Spasm 0-1   NC-NC 0.7201 0.1266  0.0618 0.0618 .
## 3 Spasm 0-1   Tuber 0.5727 0.1016  0.0017 0.0017 *

- Random standard deviation (0.11). So ~25% of the residual.

Analysis of variance

rm(p1, p2)
emm.inter <- emmeans(model.inter, ~ Spasm | Anatomy, type = "response") 

des_cont <- list("Spasm 0-1" = c(1, -1))

contrast(emm.inter, des_cont, adjust = "FDR") %>%
  data.frame()  %>%
  mutate(`(FDR)` = round(p.value,4)) %>%
  dplyr::select(-df, -z.ratio, -ratio, -SE, -p.value) -> cc.01

contrast(emm.inter, des_cont, adjust = "none") %>%
  data.frame() %>%
  dplyr::select(-df, -z.ratio) %>%
  mutate(p.value = round(p.value,4),
         ratio = round(ratio,4),
         SE = round(SE,4)) %>%
  right_join(cc.01) %>%
  mutate(`-` = case_when(`(FDR)` > 0.05 ~ ".",
                        `(FDR)` < 0.05 ~ "*"))
